    <div class="explanation">
        <h3>Why "Garbage Collector Isn't Working" is a Misdiagnosis</h3>
        <p>Your colleague observes memory growing and correctly identifies that memory isn't being reclaimed. However, attributing this to the "garbage collector not working" is a common misunderstanding. The JavaScript garbage collector (GC) is very good at its job: it reclaims memory occupied by objects that are no longer <strong>reachable</strong> from the root (e.g., global scope, current call stack).</p>

        <p>The problem demonstrated in the "Buggy Dashboard" is not that the GC isn't working, but that the objects (specifically, the DOM elements and their associated event listeners/closures) are <strong>still reachable</strong> even after the widget is visually removed from the dashboard. This happens because:</p>

        <ol>
            <li>
                <strong>Unremoved Event Listeners:</strong> When an event listener is attached to a DOM element (e.g., with <code>addEventListener</code>), the browser creates an internal reference from the DOM element to the listener function (and its closure). If you remove the DOM element from the document but don't explicitly remove the listener, the listener function (and any variables it closes over) can still be referenced by the detached DOM element. Even if the detached DOM element itself is eligible for GC, if the listener function holds a reference to other objects (like the widget's internal state or even the widget's own DOM element), those objects also become unreachable.
                <div class="code-block">
                    <p><strong>Leaking Code Snippet:</strong></p>
                    <pre><code>
const leakingWidgetDiv = document.createElement('div');
leakingWidgetDiv.addEventListener('click', () => {
    // This closure captures 'leakingWidgetDiv'.
    // Even if leakingWidgetDiv is removed from DOM,
    // this listener still holds a reference to it.
    console.log('Leaking widget clicked:', leakingWidgetDiv.id);
    leakingWidgetDiv.classList.toggle('expanded');
});
                    </code></pre>
                </div>
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Direct DOM References in JavaScript:</strong> If your JavaScript code keeps a direct reference to a DOM element (e.g., in a global array or a long-lived object) even after that element is removed from the DOM, the element cannot be garbage collected.
                <div class="code-block">
                    <p><strong>Leaking Code Snippet:</strong></p>
                    <pre><code>
const globalLeakingWidgets = []; // A global array storing all widget DOM elements
function addLeakingWidget() {
    const widgetDiv = createLeakingWidgetElement();
    globalLeakingWidgets.push(widgetDiv); // Reference stored here
    dashboard.appendChild(widgetDiv);
}
function removeLeakingWidget(widgetDiv) {
    dashboard.removeChild(widgetDiv);
    // No removal from globalLeakingWidgets array!
    // The widgetDiv is still reachable via globalLeakingWidgets.
}
                    </code></pre>
                </div>
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Closures Capturing Large Objects:</strong> Even if the DOM element itself is GC'd, if a closure (like an event listener) is still reachable and that closure captures a large object or many objects from its lexical environment, those captured objects will also remain in memory.
            </li>
        </ol>

        <p>In essence, the GC isn't "not working"; it's simply not collecting objects that are still considered "alive" because there's an active reference path to them. The fix involves explicitly breaking these reference paths when a widget is removed.</p>

        <h3>How the "Fixed Dashboard" Addresses the Problem:</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <strong>Removing Event Listeners:</strong> Before a widget's DOM element is removed from the document, its associated event listeners are explicitly removed using <code>removeEventListener</code>. This breaks the reference from the DOM element to the listener function.
                <div class="code-block">
                    <p><strong>Fixed Code Snippet:</strong></p>
                    <pre><code>
function createFixedWidgetElement(id) {
    const fixedWidgetDiv = document.createElement('div');
    // ... setup ...
    const clickHandler = () => {
        console.log('Fixed widget clicked:', id);
        fixedWidgetDiv.classList.toggle('expanded');
    };
    fixedWidgetDiv.addEventListener('click', clickHandler);
    // Store the handler so we can remove it later
    fixedWidgetDiv.clickHandler = clickHandler; 
    return fixedWidgetDiv;
}

function removeFixedWidget(widgetDiv) {
    widgetDiv.removeEventListener('click', widgetDiv.clickHandler); // Crucial!
    fixedDashboard.removeChild(widgetDiv);
}
                    </code></pre>
                </div>
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Nullifying References:</strong> If you maintain an array or object of references to your widgets (e.g., for state management), ensure that when a widget is removed, its entry in that array/object is also cleared (e.g., by <code>splice</code> or <code>delete</code>). In this simple example, we don't maintain explicit JS references to the DOM elements in a global array, so the primary leak is the event listener. However, if we did, we'd clear them.
            </li>
        </ul>

        <p>By actively cleaning up these references, we ensure that when a widget is removed from the DOM, it truly becomes unreachable, allowing the garbage collector to reclaim its memory.</p>

